(-b ± sqrt(D)) / (2a)\n\nSubstituting the values of a, b, and D:\nx = (-(-5) ± sqrt(1)) / (2*1)\nx = (5 ± 1) / 2\n\nSo, the two roots are:\nx1 = (5 + 1) / 2 = 6 / 2 = 3\nx2 = (5 - 1) / 2 = 4 / 2 = 2\n\n### Step 4: Verify using Vieta's formulas\nAccording to Vieta's formulas, for a quadratic equation ax^2 + bx + c = 0 with roots x1 and x2:\n- x1 + x2 = -b/a\n- x1 * x2 = c/a\n\nSubstituting the values of a, b, c, x1, and x2:\n- x1 + x2 = 3 + 2 = 5 = -(-5)/1 = 5/1 (matches the formula)\n- x1 * x2 = 3 * 2 = 6 = 6/1 (matches the formula)\n\nBoth conditions are satisfied, verifying that x1 = 3 and x2 = 2 are indeed the roots of the equation x^2 - 5x + 6 = 0.\n\nAlternatively, we could have also factored the quadratic equation directly:\nx^2 - 5x + 6 = (x - 2)(x - 3) = 0\nThis gives us the roots x = 2 and x = 3, which matches our solution \n\nVerify the solution and respond with JSON only."}], 'model': 'llama-3.3-70b-versatile', 'max_tokens': 600, 'temperature': 0.1}}
